 to leave his $700k per year private equity job in Hong Kong to come join h=
is ragtag crew in Hangzhou. Joe immediately got to work trying to raise mon=
ey for the business.=C2=A0
He set Alibaba up as a Variable Interest Entity in the Cayman Islands, whic=
h would allow it to take money from foreign investors, and organized a trip=
 for the two to Silicon Valley. The trip was unsuccessful, but right around=
 that time, China.com IPO=E2=80=99d at a $1 billion valuation, and the Chin=
a rush was on.=C2=A0
When they got home, Joe called up an old friend, Shirley Lin, who was leadi=
ng Goldman=E2=80=99s tech investments in Asia. They negotiated a deal for G=
oldman to acquire a majority stake in Alibaba for $5 million. Jack pushed b=
ack at a 50/50 split, and Lin agreed, but the Goldman investment committee =
decided it didn=E2=80=99t want all that risk =F0=9F=A4=A6=F0=9F=8F=BB=E2=80=
=8D=E2=99=82=EF=B8=8F. Goldman kept 33% and syndicated out 17% to GGV, Vent=
ure TDF, Fidelity Growth Partners, Investor AB (Joe=E2=80=99s old employer)=
, and Transpac.=C2=A0
(Goldman would sell its stake in 2004, after Lin left the company, for $22 =
million. The 6x return isn=E2=80=99t bad, until you calculate that 33% of A=
libaba is worth $210 billion today! =F0=9F=A4=A6=F0=9F=8F=BB=E2=80=8D=E2=99=
=82=EF=B8=8F The lesson: never sell!)
Money in the bank, Alibaba got back to building, signing up more than forty=
 thousand users by the end of the year largely by keeping the site free. At=
 the time, the site was little more than a directory and message board, as =
captured by the Wayback Machine:=C2=A0
The fight for talent in a hot China tech market was fierce, but Alibaba had=
 an advantage: Hangzhou. Being in a Tier 2 city gave Alibaba access to chea=
p talent with few other options and cheap real estate (they signed a 200k s=
f office lease for $80k per year, or $0.40/sf, in 2000). In a bit of foresh=
adowing, Jack highlighted another benefit:=C2=A0
Even though the infrastructure is not as good as in Shanghai, it=E2=80=99s =
better to be as far away from the central government as possible.
Money became even less of an issue for Alibaba just a couple of months late=
r, when, in January 2000, SoftBank led a $20 million investment [https://em=
ail.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uxCAMhU8zLCN-k7Bg0Vn0Aj1ABMGToUkgBadRbl9msqhl=
GYNlnt43WoQp5dNsqSB5lQHPDUyEoyyACJnsBfIQvGEt74WSmngjPetVT0IZHhlgtWExmHcg2-6=
WMFoMKb43KOWKPI3iTmvaQisUFe7hlXDU9mPvGLRcW3rp2t0HiCMY-IV8pghkMU_ErdzEx41_1j=
yOoznKdzOmtd5sxjAuUGr7ddey55Rr3fZd10nNOkGCqS-MshpCKcka1vycCub9EfN8k3SdeFN2V=
9CO8-tLkk1M6FIOcarj-WlXWN6Damuo57rHgOcA0boF_OUYL3BvBsMEEXIF6geLFRejohNCMq3Y=
5bAiEYxTxVpKqrJPdSv-i_4BdrmD4g] for 30% of Alibaba. As I wrote in Masa Madn=
ess [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkEluxCAQRU_T7NpiMB4WLLLJNRCYajeyA=
QeKRL59SFtKFAmoxVfx9N9iENaUT3WkguTn0XgeoCJ8lR0QIZNaIGvvFBv4JGQ_E6d6xyY5EV_0=
IwME43eFuQI5qt39YtCn-NqglEvyVOIxWmPoxIG7caSMzZxbOcBgxTwZN19cU52HuICCT8hnikB=
29UQ8yk283fh7OzGhTdnHtSvVFjTL1i0ptOBoN5hi7sG4CKXcxWKJV5xy1miMCSl71rHu45Sw1U=
fM262nYeX__iFZ_QJavD1NgP0VtFq6zVCjx1NDNHYHdzXGS9zLgV4hQm5CnTbYdDEqRiF6Nkt2N=
WxKBONUsoGSRnapbcU_6DfUX4b_], Masayoshi Son led the deal himself after list=
ening to Jack speak for just five minutes. At the time, Jack said, =E2=80=
=9CWe didn't talk about revenues; we didn't even talk about a business mode=
l. We just talked about a shared vision. Both of us make quick decisions.=
=E2=80=9D
Reflecting back at Alibaba=E2=80=99s 2014 IPO, the notoriously eccentric So=
n said, =E2=80=9CIt was the look in his eye, it was an =E2=80=98animal smel=
l.=E2=80=99 =E2=80=A6 I invested based on my sense of smell.=E2=80=9D His n=
ose was on point: when Alibaba IPO=E2=80=99d, the investment was worth $60 =
billion, a 3,000x return. That investment is responsible for SoftBank=E2=80=
=99s Vision Fund, fwiw.=C2=A0
The cash came in just as the dot com bubble was about to burst, and allowed=
 Alibaba to keep building. It surpassed 300,000 members in the summer of 20=
00. In July, Forbes made Jack the first Chinese business person on the cove=
r in fifty years, and in August, The Economist profiled Jack in a piece cal=
led The Jack Who Would Be King [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uhD=
AMhU8z2YHyAymzyKKbXgMFYiAFEpo4Rdy-nmFRy7ItW09P_kaLMMd0mSNmZK_S43WACXDmDRAhs=
ZIh9d4ZoWWn2ubJnGmc6NqO-dxPCWC3fjOYCrCjDJsfLfoY3grOZcsWo7W0chpdJ7nSHTxBW861=
bpxU04dw-va1xXkIIxj4hXTFAGwzC-KRH-rzIb8oz_OsYYwh7j5jPcaddkPJPkDONErOOTXevea=
GCi5Qfdtxrc4lVmcsm6sGqFYfZuaN5FJwQaHathG1qH-uFtYyhbQ-Gr7Pss5lyEjylxNLJkQcYi=
IxndfF7rC9D_RzT30vwePVQ7DDBu7GgTfVN6B-hgCJaLveIrEUXH0o1YhnK-73iZcSkrdCc0bOL=
pIq_Jv-AQXDjv0].
Despite member growth and press, though, Alibaba wasn=E2=80=99t making any =
money. It was becoming bloated, with engineering offices in Silicon Valley.=
 So Jack brought in a former GE exec, Savio Kwan, who killed the US office =
and figured out how to start making money.=C2=A0
Since the Chinese market was so nascent, the Alibaba team realized it could=
n=E2=80=99t just copy the US business model of charging businesses to list =
and taking a cut of transactions. Instead, Alibaba gave away the product an=
d transactions for free and charged sellers for better placement. It worked=
=2E=C2=A0
For the first time, in early 2002, Alibaba turned a profit. Just when thing=
s were looking up, though, Alibaba would face two of its biggest challenges=
 yet.
To learn about Jack=E2=80=99s strategic chops, Alibaba=E2=80=99s Businesses=
, how it compares to Amazon, the Ant Group fiasco, investing in China, and =
what to do about BABA:
Important Note:=C2=A0This is not investment advice. I am not a registered i=
nvestment adviser. Everything in this essay is for learning and laughs only=
