eal himself after listening to Jack speak for just five minutes. At the tim=
e, Jack said, &#8220;We didn't talk about revenues; we didn't even talk abo=
ut a business model. We just talked about a shared vision. Both of us make =
quick decisions.&#8221;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Reflecting back at Alibaba&#8217;s 2014=
 IPO, the notoriously eccentric Son said, &#8220;It was the look in his eye=
, it was an &#8216;animal smell.&#8217; &#8230; I invested based on my sens=
e of smell.&#8221; His nose was on point: when Alibaba IPO&#8217;d, the inv=
estment was <strong>worth $60 billion, a 3,000x return</strong>. That inves=
tment is responsible for SoftBank&#8217;s Vision Fund, fwiw.&nbsp;</p><p st=
yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em =
0;">The cash came in just as the dot com bubble was about to burst, and all=
owed Alibaba to keep building. It surpassed 300,000 members in the summer o=
f 2000. In July, Forbes made Jack the first Chinese business person on the =
